06627nam a22007215i 9781847422033DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20092009xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a9781847422033  a(DE-B1597)646099  a(OCoLC)436916493  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aPOL0290002bisacsh04a361.94100aCASE Studies on Poverty, Place and Policy. Towards a more equal society? :bPoverty, inequality and policy since 1997 /ced. by John Hills, Tom Sefton, Kitty Stewart. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (432 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCASE Studies on Poverty, Place and Policy00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes on contributors -- tIntroduction -- tDimensions of policy and outcomes -- tPoverty, inequality and redistribution -- t‘A scar on the soul of Britain’: child poverty and disadvantage under New Labour -- tEducation: New Labour’s top priority -- tMore equal working lives? An assessment of New Labour policies -- tNew Labour and unequal neighbourhoods -- tHealth inequalities: a persistent problem -- tPensions and income security in later life -- tEthnic inequalities: another 10 years of the same? -- tMigration, migrants and inequality -- tCross-cutting issues -- tMoving in the right direction? Public attitudes to poverty, inequality and redistribution -- tInequality and the devolved administrations: Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland -- tPoverty, inequality and child well-being in international context: still bottom of the pack? -- tWhere do we go from here? -- tThe Equality and Human Rights Commission: a new point of departure in the battle against discrimination and disadvantage -- tFuture pressures: intergenerational links, wealth, demography and sustainability -- tConclusions: climbing every mountain or retreating from the foothills? -- tReferences0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen New Labour came to power in 1997, its leaders asked for it to be judged after ten years on its success in making Britain 'a more equal society'. As it approaches the end of an unprecedented third term in office, this book asks whether Britain has indeed moved in that direction. The highly successful earlier volume A more equal society? was described by Polly Toynbee as the LSE's mighty judgement on inequality. Now this second volume by the same team of authors provides an independent assessment of the success or otherwise of New Labour's policies over a longer period. It provides: · consideration by a range of expert authors of a broad set of indicators and policy areas affecting poverty, inequality and social exclusion; · analysis of developments up to the third term on areas including income inequality, education, employment, health inequalities, neighbourhoods, minority ethnic groups, children and older people; · an assessment of outcomes a decade on, asking whether policies stood up to the challenges, and whether successful strategies have been sustained or have run out of steam; chapters on migration, social attitudes, the devolved administrations, the new Equality and Human Rights Commission, and future pressures. The book is essential reading for academic and student audiences with an interest in contemporary social policy, as well as for all those seeking an objective account of Labour's achievements in power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aEqualityzGreat Britain. 0aPublic welfarezGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aBurchardt, Tania, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvandrou, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalkingham, Jane